ng of 2006. GEMS is intended to cover those of its employees who are currently insured with other schemes \'96 it is estimated that there are upwards of 60 medical schemes that provide coverage for government employees - as well as those, predominantly low-in
come, government employees who are presently uninsured and, as such, are dependent on the public healthcare system. There are currently about 1.1 million lives in the public sector. It is estimated that some 400 000 government employees are not covered by 
any medical scheme.  It appears that the intention is }}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 to phase in GEMS, focusing first on migrating already insured government employees from their current schemes to GEMS.  The second phase will focus on persuading those government employees who are prese
ntly uninsured to take up one of GEMS\'92 low-cost options.{\super \chftn{\*\footnote \chftn\pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch{\*\cs28\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up8\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\loch}{\rtlch \ltrch\loch  }{\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs20\lang2057\i0\b0 See transcript page 321}}}
{\*\cs28\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af9\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  We were informed that government intends membership of GEMS to be voluntary \'96 however a subsidy will not be made available to employees who choose to belong to a scheme other than GEMS.}
