\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s14{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs20\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs20\lang2057\loch\f7\fs20\lang2057 }}
{\*\cs28\cf0{\*\updnprop5801}\up10\rtlch\af9\afs24\lang255\ltrch\dbch\af9\langfe255\hich\f1\fs24\lang7177\loch\f1\fs24\lang7177 }  Thus, it is plain to see that the hospital group has literally surrounded itself with the key platforms of hospital referral \'96 an ambulance service, a pathology service, a dialysis unit and primary care services.  W
ith respect to primary care services \'96 the area that we are called upon to examine in this transaction \'96 it is important to recall that it is not only through Netcare\'92s control of the Medicross clinic network that its relationship with primary care provide
rs is effected.  It is also cemented through Netpartner and Netdirect.  Note, as already elaborated, that Netpartner is controlled as to 48% by Netcare and as to 52% by some 9000 healthcare practitioners, the majority of whom are primary care providers.  N
etpartner is, at 17.5% (at the time of the merger hearings), the largest single shareholder of the listed entity, Netcare.  Netpartner wholly controls Netdirect, which offers full risk capitation products including a network of primary care providers who s
ervice the primary care component of the full risk product.  It is to be expected that many of the 800 members of the Netdirect network of primary care providers are to be counted amongst the 9000 medical practitioners who hold equity in Netpartner and, th
rough Netpartner, in Netcare itself.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 
