\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f7\lang2057\f7\fs24\f7\lang1025\qj\tx540 216.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls1\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 The interests and concerns of the industry players \'96 Davidson and Strauss \'96 who professed concern at the vertical dimensions of this transaction are reasonably clear. Mr. Davidson, who represents a competing hospital group, is concerned that the Netcare-al
igned practitioners will favour the Netcare hospitals and this in one of three ways.  First he fears that these practitioners will \'91under-refer\'92 patients to Netcare\'92s competitors or, conversely, that they will \'91over-refer\'92 to Netcare hospitals.  In a conte
xt where all the private hospitals experience significant excess capacity this is, of course, a serious concern for Netcare\'92s competitors. Secondly, he fears that, in certain circumstances, the Netcare-aligned practitioners will {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i over}-refer to Netcare\'92s com
petitors or, conversely, {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i under}-refer to Netcare hospitals. Thirdly, and a variant of the second concern, he is concerned that the Netcare-aligned practitioners may {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i selectively} refer as between the three competing hospital groups so as to favour the commerc
ial interests of Netcare.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li540\ri0\lin540\rin0\fi-540\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f7\lang2057\f7\fs24\f7\lang1025\qj\tx540 217.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls1\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 These concerns which, on the face of it, appear mutually exclusive, do indeed arise under different incentive regimes.  Firstly, where a patient is on a full fee-for-service option, that is, where each engagement with a primary, secondary and tertiary prov
ider is covered by medical insurance (albeit subject to managed care interventions such as hospital pre-authorisation), then, while the incentive of each provider is to retain the patient as long as is feasible (that is to \'91over-treat\'92 at each stage), once
 a referral is medically indicated, then the incentive of the referring primary care practitioner is to refer the patient to an allied secondary and tertiary provider.  In this incentive regime, the secondary and tertiary provider will be happy to accept t
his referral because the medical insurance cover of the patient fully covers both of these treatment stages.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f7\lang2057\f7\fs24\f7\lang1025\qj\tx540 218.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls1\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 Secondly, however, where a patient is on a capitated primary care option but has fee-for-service cover at the secondary and tertiary stages, the incentives shift significantly at the primary stage of treatment but remain the same at the secondary and terti
ary stages.  The primary care provider is incentivised to refer the patient as soon as possible \'96 to \'91under-treat\'92 - but the incentives of the secondary and tertiary providers remain as outlined in the previous paragraph.  That is to say, the secondary and
 tertiary providers are pleased to accept the patient because her treatment at this stage is fully insured by her fee-for-service cover at these stages. }
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s15{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ql\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f7\lang2057\f7\fs24\f7\lang1025\qj\tx540 219.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls1\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 In the two incentive regimes described above, a primary practitioner aligned to a secondary and tertiary provider will be incentivised to support his ally.  That is, he will refer his patient to his allied secondary and tertiary provider.  The second of th
e regimes described \'96 that capitated primary care and fee-for-service secondary and tertiary care \'96 is particularly attractive to the allied secondary and tertiary providers because the primary care provider is incentivised to \'91under-treat\'92 or, what is the
 same thing, \'91over-refer\'92.}
\par \pard\plain \ltrpar\s1\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\li540\ri0\lin540\rin0\fi-540\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 
\par \pard\plain {\listtext\pard\plain \li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\f7\lang2057\f7\fs24\f7\lang1025\qj\tx540 220.\tab}\ilvl0 \ltrpar\s1\qj\tx540{\*\hyphen2\hyphlead2\hyphtrail2\hyphmax0}\ls1\li360\ri0\lin360\rin0\fi-360\rtlch\af7\afs24\lang1025\ltrch\dbch\af7\langfe255\hich\f7\fs24\lang2057\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057 {\rtlch \ltrch\loch\f7\fs24\lang2057\i0\b0 The third incentive regime is where the patient is on \'91full-risk capitation\'92, that is where each provider \'96 primary, secondary and tertiary \'96 is capitated. In this regime, each provider is incentivised to under-treat, that is, over-refer.  Accordingly here
, a primary care provider allied to a secondary and tertiary provider is incentivised both to under-treat and to (over) refer to the {\rtlch\ltrch\dbch\hich\i\loch\i competitors} of his allies at the secondary and tertiary stages.  As already indicated, Mr. Davidson expressed concern that 
